Discoloration and food caused by fungal species.

To apply color to a wall or to make a painting or drawing.

A protection cover for a sharp blade (of a sword or knife).

To spread (a substance) across a surface by rubbing.
To emit smoke (such as something which burns).

To lengthen by pulling.
To intentionally hit something with a sharp blow or to impel, usually with a hand.

Giving milk to babies and young children with milk from a woman's breast.

To attach an animal to something to prevent that it leaves.
To establish connection between two or more things.
Being not loose.
A metallic element with symbol Sn, occurring in cassiterite. It is a malleable silvery-white metal.
A metallic element with symbol Sn or a thin sheet of steel coated with tin to prevent rusting.
Emit a sound suggestive of a tinkle.
A thin sheet of steel coated with tin to prevent rusting; used to make cans etc.
Any portable device that produces light.
To put something to trial, to test whether something works as expected.

To fall down accidentally.

To change the direction one is facing while lying in bed, on the floor, or similar.
Shine with flickering light.
To uncover; to show and display that which was hidden.
To loosen, as something interlaced or knotted; to disengage the parts of. To unbind, to free from restraint.
To employ an object, often to reach a certain goal; to put into service.
To make warm or warmer.
To move one's hand or arm in a waving motion, with or without holding something like a flag.
The process by which one produces something (sometimes also in exchange for money).

A tool consisting of a stick (usually out of wood) and a bigger, slightly humped surface (usually out of metal), which is used to move material such as earth, snow, grain, etc. from one place to another.

Separating the grain from the straw or husks by beating.

A species of palm tree in the genus Euterpe cultivated for its fruit and hearts of palm.
A derivative of the achiote trees of tropical regions of the Americas used as a red food coloring and as a flavoring.

A plant that grows in the hot, dry parts of the southern US and South America. There are many different types of agave and the plants have thick long or rounded leaves with sharp points on them, and tall flowers.
It is a perennial high grown grass native to Asia, Australia and Africa.
The edible and cultivated fruit of the tree Prunus dulcis in the family Rosaceae. It resembles a nut and can be sold shelled or unshelled.
A spring vegetable.
A kind of poplar tree (genus Populus; section Populus).
Type of palm (Attalea speciosa) widely spread in Brazil; its fruit is edible and used to produce oil and medicine
A group of woody perennial evergreen plants in the true grass family Poaceae, subfamily Bambusoideae, tribe Bambuseae.
The tropical treelike plant which bears clusters of bananas. The plant, of the genus Musa, has large, elongated leaves.
A tropical Indian fig tree, Ficus benghalensis, that has many aerial roots.
Genus of big trees (Adansonia) from the mallow family, growing in tropical countries.

To produce or yield fruits.
Any tree of the genus Fagus, of temperate regions, having a smooth gray bark and bearing small, edible, triangular nuts.
Triploid banana cultivars originating from the African Great Lakes region.
A vine of the species 'Piper betle' whose leaves are chewed for its medicinal properties.
The seed of the areca palm (Areca catechu).
Fagopyrum tataricum, a domesticated plant similar to the (sweet) buckwheat.
To bear flowers or to start bearing flowers; to blossom.
Perennial flowering plants with indigo-coloured berries from the section Cyanococcus.
Edible seed of a tree (bertholletia excelsa); used to produce medicine
Native Brazilian tree  (Cedrela odorata). Its wood is often used for canoes
Bean of the plant Vicia faba, also known as fava bean. It is typically large, of a pale green colour, and edible.
(Fagopyrum esculentum) An annual plant with clusters of small pinkish white flowers and small edible triangular seeds which are used whole or ground into flour.
A plant resembling a small tree, but has no, and will never develop, a stem.
A mamber of the plant family Cactaceae.

(Not to confuse with gourd) a plant from the family Bignoniaceae, native to tropical America. It has a form of a small tree, producing fruit of the globular shape. It is also known under the name of Crescentia cujete and its fruits are mostly used to make utensils, containers, and musical instruments.
Domesticated root vegetable usually orange or red in colour.
A tropical evergreen tree that produces the cashew seed and the cashew apple.
Shrub (Manihot esculenta) whose roots are rich in starch.
Common designation of several species of the Cecropia genus (genus Cecropia)
The outer shell or coating of a seed.
Any north temperate fagaceous tree of the genus Castanea, such as Castanea sativa, which produce flowers in long catkins and nuts in a prickly bur.
Species of flowering plant in the Arecaceae family, trunked palm tree which is endemic to the Juan Fernández Islands archipielago in the southeast Pacific Ocean west of Chile.
The fruits of a plant in the citrus genus. They have a leathery rind surrounding segments filled with pulp vesicles.
The aromatic flower bud of a clove tree, used as a spice.
A plant in the family Erythroxylaceae, native to western South America.
The dried and fully fermented fatty seed of Theobroma cacao, from which cocoa solids and cocoa butter are extracted.
A tropical tree with feathery leaves which bears coconuts.
The large hard-shelled oval nut with a fibrous husk of the cocos palm.
The fruit of a pine or fir tree.
Annual herb in the family Apiaceae.
A field in which corn is grown.
The outer covering of a corncob.
A composite plant, Centaurea cyanus, having narrow leaves and blue flower heads.
The cotton-looking seeds of a cottonwood tree that are spread around by the wind during the shedding season (usually from late spring to early summer).
The red and typically sour berry of several evergreen shrubs in the family Ericaceae.
The edible fruit of the cucumber plant, having a green rind and crisp white flesh.
A common name for various coniferous trees or shrubs of northern temperate regions that belong to the family Cupressaceae.
A species of the genus Taraxacum, a large genus of flowering plants in the family Asteraceae.
The sweet, edible fruit of the date palm Phoenix dactylifera of the family Arecaceae.
A piece of wood with a point used for making holes in the ground for seeds, seedlings or small bulbs.
To move earth, rocks, etc. out of the way, usually to create a hole.
A rod shaped implement used by the aboriginal people of Australia to dig yam and as a combat weapon.

A long, narrow excavation artificially dug in the ground; especially an open and usually unpaved waterway, channel, or trench for conveying water for drainage or irrigation, and usually smaller than a canal. Some ditches may be natural watercourses.
The dog-rose (rosa canina) is a variable climbing wild rose species native to Europe, northwest Africa and western Asia and whose fruit is known as hip.
The upper part of grain plants.
A tall tree with broad leaves.
Tree or wood for plants with capsule fruiting bodies belonging to closely related genera found across Australia.
A severe shortage of food, as through crop failure or over population. It may be due to poor harvests following drought, floods, earthquake, war, social conflict, etc.
To cut down a tree.
Delimitation for an area.
Any member of a large group of vascular plants in the family Filices who have neither flowers nor seeds.
A dry field rather than a flooded paddy field.
A limited area of land with grass or crops growing on it, which is usually surrounded by fences or closely planted bushes when it is part of a farm.
Eleusine coracana, a herbaceous plant characteristic for the hability to withstand cultivation at high altitudes.
An evergreen coniferous tree of the genus Abies.
In Amazonia, a kind of root is apparently used as fish poison.
A plant with blue flowers that is cultivated for its stem to make linen or its seeds to make oil, or a material made from the fibers of the flax plant.
A plant with blue flowers that is cultivated for its stem to make linen or its seeds to make oil.

Either a species of trees in the family Rubiaceae native to the tropical forests of Americas or its fruit (also referred to as “genipap”). A Genipa tree typically has large smooth or hairy leaves and ovoid-shaped fruit with large and flat seeds.
A herbaceous perennial which grows annual stems about a meter tall bearing narrow green leaves and yellow flowers.

A type of rice grown mainly in Southeast and East Asia and the eastern parts of South Asia, which has opaque grains, very low amylose content, and is especially sticky when cooked. Also called oryza sativa var. glutinosa, sticky rice, sweet rice or waxy rice.
Either a gourd or a melon.

A plant belonging to the family Cucurbitaceae, native to tropical Africa. It represents a creeping vine, usually grown for its fruits that, as a rule, can have a variety of shapes: from rounded to globular, bottle- or club-shaped or even slim and coiled.
Edible, starchy seeds of the grass family (Graminae) usable as food by man and his livestock.
A building for storing threshed grain.

The fruit of the pomelo tree, Citrus maxima, of the family Rutaceae, or the fruit of the grapefruit tree, Citrus x paradisi, a citrus hybrid which originated from crossing pomelos and oranges. Due to the recent origin of the grapefruit and the close genetic relatedness between both fruits, they are often not differentiated lexically.
A climbing plant that produces grapes and belongs to the family Vitaceae.

A very large and widespread family of Monocotyledoneae, with more than 10.000 species, most of which are herbaceous, but a few are woody. The stems are jointed, the long, narrow leaves originating at the nodes. The flowers are inconspicuous, with a much reduced perianth, and are wind-pollinated or cleistogamous.
Areas where the vegetation is dominated by grasses.
A green (i.e., not mature) oval nut with a fibrous husk of the cocos palm, used as source of coconut water.
A nutlike fruit from the plant Arachis hypogaea that grows on long stems under ground.
An agricultural implement consisting of many spikes, tines or discs dragged across the soil.
To gather the ripened crop.
Any of various shrubs and small trees of the genus Crataegus having small, apple-like fruits and thorny branches.

A tall annual herb, Cannabis sativa, native to Asia.
A flowering plant that is valued for its medical properties.

A species of tree in the fig, mulberry and breadfruit family (Moraceae).
A tall grain-bearing plant of the Poaceae family; coixseed; yi yi.
Either the Bombax ceiba (tree with red flowers), or the Calotropis procera, or the Ceiba pentandra.

A coniferous  tree, of genus Larix, having deciduous leaves.
A long rope with a sliding loop on one end, generally used in ranching to catch cattle and horses.
Fruit with yellow rind and acidic/sour juice.
A small seed that is dried and used in cooking.

A liana is any of various long-stemmed, woody vines that are rooted in the soil at ground level and use trees, as well as other means of vertical support, to climb up to the canopy to get access to well-lit areas of the fores .
The inner most layer of bark (particularly from a tree).
A green citrus fruit.
Species of the genus Borassus of fan palms.
One of two species of aquatic plant in the family Nelumbonaceae.
A species of trees in the mahogany family Meliaceae, native to tropical Africa and Madagascar.
A type of grain of the species Zea mays.
A small citrus tree with fruit resembling other oranges. Mandarin oranges are usually eaten plain or in fruit salads.
The fruit from the Mango tree.
Any of various tropical evergreen trees or shrubs that grow in shallow coastal water; Plants of the Rhizophoraceae family and/or of the genus Rhizophora.
Flour made of the cassava plant or root.
Shrub (Manihot esculenta) whose roots are rich in starch.
Species of the genus Arctostaphylos; evergreen shrubs or small trees present in the chaparral biome of western North America.
A group of trees belonging to the genus acer.
A group of small-seeded species of cereal crops, widely grown around the world for food and fodder.
Mauritia flexuosa, a palm tree of the family Arecaceae, common to tropical regions of South America.
Species of the genus Moringa, widely cultivated in tropical and subtropical areas and used in herbal medicine.
Any plant of the class Bryophyta, occurring in nearly all damp habitats.
An ear-shaped edible fungus that belongs to the species of Auriculariaceae and is used in medicine and culinary.
A common name for several species of aromatic plants in the genus Artemisia.
An organism belonging to a family of Basidiomycetes that are characterized by the production of spores on gills.
Any of numerous plants having stinging hairs that cause skin irritation on contact (especially of the genus Urtica or family Urticaceae). [B:33]

Any tree of the genus Quercus in the order Fagales, characterized by simple, usually lobed leaves, scaly winter buds, a star-shaped pith, and its fruit, the acorn, which is a nut; the wood is tough, hard, and durable, generally having a distinct pattern.
A species of grass (Avena sativa) grown for its seed.
A flowering plant in the mallow (Malvaceae) family valued for its edible pods; okro, ochro; ladies' fingers.
A small tree species native to Asia from the Himalayas through southern China.
Any of various evergreen trees from the family Palmae or Arecaceae, which are mainly found in the tropics.
Palm-like, dioecious trees and shrubs native to the Old World tropics and subtropics.
The flower of the Peach Tree.
A species of palm, also know as Bactris gasipaes, native to the tropical forests of Central and South America.
The tree that bears peaches as fruits.
The soft, sweet, juicy fruit of the peach tree, usually with a red or orange skin, yellow flesh and a large stone inside.
A species in the family Fabaceae (commonly known as the bean, pea or legume family).
A fruit produced by the pear tree.
Edible fruit of a number of species of trees of the genus Diospyros in the ebony wood family.
Evergreen coniferous tree of the genus Pinus.
A device consisting of a mouthpiece, a long pipe stem and a pipe bowl, that is used to smoke tobacco.
To put a plant in the ground so that it strikes root and grows.

A plant of the genus Plantago, with a rosette of sessile leaves about 10 cm long with a narrow part instead of a petiole, and with a spike inflorescence with the flower spacing varying widely among the species.
Any of various deciduous trees of the genus Populus.
A flowering plant in the family Rutaceae.
A squash fruit of the Cucurbita genus, most commonly orange in colour when ripe and traditionally used during Halloween.
To put livestock into a field or pasture or meadow to graze.
An edible root vegetable of the Brassicaceae family that was domesticated in Europe in pre-Roman times.
A perennial shrub native to Eastern Asia, with broad leaves and clusters of greenish flowers.
The edible, berry-like fruit of a multitude of plant species in the genus Rubus of the family Rosaceae, most typically red, small and sweet.

A member of the genus Ribes in the gooseberry family Grossulariaceae, native to parts of western Europe (France, Belgium, Netherlands, Germany, and northern Italy). It is a deciduous shrub normally growing to 1-1.5 m tall, occasionally 2 m, with five-lobed leaves arranged spirally on the stems.
A flour made from finely milled rice, distinct from rice starch which is produced by steeping rice in lye; rice powder.
The husk of rice seeds.
An erect grass, Oryza sativa, that grows in East Asia on wet ground and has drooping flower spikes and yellow oblong edible grains that become white when polished.
The seedling of a rice plant.
The dry stalks of the rice plant.
Seeds of the rice plant (Oryza sativa) used as food.
A ripe (i.e., mature) oval nut with a fibrous husk of the cocos palm, used as source of coconut meat.
A showy flower of any of a genus (Rosa of the family Rosaceae, the rose family).
Biennial plant from the genus Secale of the family Poaceae, used as a cereal or for forage.
A farm tool consisting of a long bent blade attached to a shaft, that is designed for cutting straws of grass or grain from an upright position.
A flowering plant in the genus Sesamum.
Tree of the Sapotaceae family,indigenous to Africa, commonly known as shea tree. The shea fruits are oil-rich seed from which shea butter is extracted.
A woody perennial plant, smaller than a tree, with several major branches arising from near the base of the main stem.
To inhale smoke from for example a cigarette or a cigar.
Tool having a flat and sharp metal tip and a wooden handle used to break, dig and move the earth.
The fruiting body of a grain plant.
Any of various large coniferous evergreen trees from the genus Picea, found in northern temperate and boreal regions.
Soft, red fruit with yellow seeds on its surface.
A tropical grass of the genus Saccharum having stout, fibrous, jointed stalks, the sap of which is a source of sugar.
Common name for several palm species used to produce sugar, especially Arenga pinnata.
The flower of teh Osmanthus Fragrans.
A species native to Asia from the Himalayas through southern China (Guizhou, Sichuan, Yunnan) to Taiwan and southern Japan and southeast Asia as far south as Cambodia and Thailand.
A tropical tree, native to Africa, including Sudan and parts of the Madagascar dry deciduous forests.
A sharp and hard structure that grows on a plant.
Leaves of certain varieties of the tobacco plant, cultivated and harvested to make cigarettes, cigars, snuff, for smoking in pipes or for chewing.
Either any  perennial plant with an elongated stem, or trunk, supporting branches and leaves, or the porous and vibrous structural tissue of which the stems of these plants consist.
The part of the body from the neck to the groin excluding the head and limbs.
A palm native to Amazon Rainforest vegetation, typical of the Pará state in Brazil.

A giant species of sedge in the plant family Cyperaceae, native to freshwater marshes. Dyed and woven, tules are used to make baskets, bowls, mats, hats, clothing, duck decoys, and even boats by Native American groups.
A rhizomatous herbaceous perennial plant (Curcuma longa) of the ginger family.
The unhusked crops of the rice plant.
Large deciduous tree (Juglans regia) in the Walnut Family (Juglandaceae) which produces an edible fruit with a hard shell and oil-rich seed.

Benincasa hispida, a species of Cucurbitaceae family, which owes its name to the wax coating of its shell. Wax gourd is cultivated for its fruit and used in both savoury and sweet dishes due to its mild flavour.
A plant that grows wild and profusely, especially when considered undesirable for agriculture.
Plant belonging to genus Triticum and to family Poaceae (also known as Gramineae).
A plant of the genus Zizania with edible grains and stem.
Any of various deciduous trees or shrubs in the genus Salix.
It is the common name for a versatile vegetable which is mainly grown in West Africa, Asia and Latin America.
Any of several large carnivorous birds in the family Accipitridae, having a powerful hooked bill and keen vision.
A plant-eating insect with long back legs that can jump very high and makes a sharp high noise using its back legs or wings.
A  burrowing rodent of the genus Dasyprocta, native to tropical America and usually having brown fur streaked with gray, similar in appearance to a guinea pig but having longer legs.
Any seabird of the family Diomedeidae. Some species are among the largest flying birds in the world.
A reptile belonging to the subfamily Alligatorinae in the family Alligatoridae in the order Crocodylia.
A member of the Urisdae family (Ursus americanus) native to North America.
Any of various large non-venomous snakes of the genus Eunectes, found mainly in northern South America.
An aquatic bird of the family Anatidae, having a flat bill and webbed feet.

Any living organism characterized by voluntary movement, the possession of cells with noncellulose cell walls and specialized sense organs enabling rapid response to stimuli, and the ingestion of complex organic substances such as plants and other animals.
A generally tubular invertebrate of the annelid phylum.
Waterfowl of the Anatidae family.
A mammal of the suborder Vermilingua having elongated snouts and feeding on ants and termites.
Any of even-toed deer-like mammals of the family Bovidae, indigenous to various parts of Africa and Eurasia.
A mound of earth made by ants as they dig their nest.
Any of the membranous-winged insects which compose the superfamily Apoidea in the order Hymenoptera characterized by a hairy body and by sucking and chewing mouthparts.

1) An underground hollow with access from the ground surface or from the sea, often found in limestone areas and on rocky coastlines.2) A natural cavity, chamber or recess which leads beneath the surface of the earth, generally in a horizontal or obliquely inclined direction. It may be in the form of a passage or a gallery, its shape depending in part on the joint pattern or structure of the rock and partly on the type of process involved in its excavation. Thus, caves worn by subterranean rivers may be different in character from, and of considerably greater extent than, a sea-cave eroded by marine waves.3) A natural underground open space, generally with a connection to the surface and large enough for a person to enter.
